{{about|the indigenous population of Bolivia|CAMBA, the bird migration treaty|China–Australia Migratory Bird Agreement|brain analysis software (CamBA)|Cambridge Brain Analysis}}
{{Expand Spanish|Camba|date=July 2011}}

'''Camba''' is a word historically used in Bolivia to refer to the indigenous population in the Eastern tropical region of the country, or to those born in the area of [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra|Santa Cruz]], [[Beni Department|Beni]], and Pando (the Eastern region of Bolivia). Nowadays, the term "Camba" is used predominately to refer to white and mestizo Bolivians largely of Spanish mixed with some Chane and other Amazonian descent born in the eastern lowlands in and around Santa Cruz de la Sierra. 

The Camba have been the focus of anthropological studies on ritualized alcohol consumption.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2010/02/15/100215fa_fact_gladwell |title=Drinking Games |last=Gladwell |first=Malcolm |authorlink=Malcolm Gladwell |date=15 February 2010 |work=The New Yorker |accessdate=17 January 2011}}</ref>  Although the Camba frequently drink 180-proof rum (considered laboratory grade in the US) their rates of alcoholism are lower than those found in most cultures.

[[Kolla people|Colla people]], who are the indigenous population that lives in Western Bolivia, have always been in conflict with Camba people due to their different customs, behavior and appearance. Therefore, it may be common to hear Camba people use the term "Colla" as a swear word or to insult the Western population as such as it is possible to hear Collas curse on cambas.

Camba may also be used as a colloquial term for "person", as in "Who is that person?" translated to "¿Quien es ese '''camba'''?" (ignores the ethnicity of the subject and does not change depending on gender as most Spanish nouns do). Such use is predominant in eastern Bolivia.

