'''Laotian Canadians''' are [[Canadians|Canadian]] citizens of [[Laos|Laotian]] origin or descent. In the [[Canada 2016 Census|2016 Census]], 24,580 people indicated Laotian ancestry.<ref name="Census2016"/> Most Lao people are Billingual because they were once under the protectorat of [[France]] (See [[French protectorate of Laos]].)

==Migration history==
Mass migration from Laos to Cambodia peaked in the late 1970s and early 1980s, consisting of both government-sponsored and privately sponsored refugees from camps in Thailand, where they had fled due to the [[Laotian Civil War]] and the final victory of the [[Pathet Lao]].<ref>{{harvnb|Van Esterik|1999|pp=902–903}}</ref> However, by the 1990s, most refugees in the camps were instead being repatriated to Laos. In total, Canada took in 12,793 Laotian refugees.<ref>{{harvnb|Van Esterik|1999|p=903}}</ref>

==Demography==
Most migrants consisted of young families; there were very few elderly among them. A significant proportion were drawn from among the [[Laotian Chinese|community of ethnic Chinese in Laos]].<ref name="Richardson16"/>

There is a community of Laotian people in [[Kitchener, Ontario]], where 995 Laotian Canadians live (0.004% of its population).<ref>[http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3530013&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Kitchener&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=3530013&TABID=1 Kitchener, City [Census subdivision], Ontario and Ontario [Province]], [[Statistics Canada]]</ref>

==Religion==
Laotian migrants in Canada mostly follow [[Theravada Buddhism]] with a mixture of animism also knowned as [[tai folk religion]] , though [[Mahayana Buddhism|Mahayana Buddhists]] are also found among those of [[Laotian Chinese]] ethnicity.<ref name="Richardson17"/> There are also a small number of Christians, perhaps 500 people, most of whom converted while living in refugee camps.<ref name="VanEsterik">{{harvnb|Van Esterik|1999}}</ref> In 1990, [[British Columbia]] had no Laotian Buddhist temple; the nearest one was a [[Laotian American]] temple in [[Seattle]].<ref name="Richardson17"/> Within Canada, Laotian Buddhist temples have also been opened in [[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec]], [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], and [[Winnipeg|Winnipeg, Manitoba]].<ref name="VanEsterik" /> There is also a handful of newly converted Laotians to [[Sunni]] [[Islam]], mostly in Montreal.

